	"body": [ 
"<p><strong>Elusive peace</strong></p><p>To the editor: The coronavirus has changed the way millions of we humans are living and has taken a heavy death toll along the way. We are saddened and mourn those who have passed.</p><p>However, having just recognized the 50th anniversary of Earth Day, we should reflect on the more than 15 million other species with whom we share the planet. Often we are caught up with our own welfare at the expense of so many others.</p><p>While great environmental gains have been made since the early 1970s, e.g. Clean Air Act, Clean Water Act, Endangered Species Act, the current administration is trying to eliminate many of these protections. We are currently witnessing Earth's sixth great extinction, with more than 30% declines in global frog species and North American migratory bird populations.</p><p>To quote Dr. Albert Schweitzer, \"Until he extends his circle of compassion to include all living things, man will not himself find peace.\" Peace continues to be elusive.</p><p><strong>R. Michael Erwin, Hendersonville</strong></p><p><strong>Sweet protection</strong></p><p>To the editor: Amid the COVID-19 virus pandemic, it's essential that everyone wear masks and other personal protective equipment whenever they are outside their home.</p><p>Paraphrasing Jackie DeShannon's song: What the world needs now is protection, sweet protection. It's the only thing that there's just too little of. What the world needs now is protection, sweet protection. No, not just for some but for everyone.</p><p>Arising out of COVID-19 is the rising number of lawsuits being brought against businesses. Social distancing is not enough to prevent the spread of COVID-19. To help protect your business from these suits, it's not enough to go around your stores disinfecting everything and/or even providing curbside pickup.</p><p>If customers are coming into your store, you need to require them to wear masks and gloves at a minimum. You also need to require All employees to do the same while they are working or on break.</p><p>No mask, no gloves = no entry.</p><p><strong>Phil Rasmussen, Hendersonville</strong></p><p><strong>More obnoxious</strong></p><p>To the editor: I have been watching Donald Trump's press conferences, and his lies, obfuscations and defensiveness are becoming more obnoxious as COVID-19 becomes worse. Among other reasons, he is using these road shows to justify eliminating oversight of the massive $2 trillion aid package that were passed by Congress.</p><p>The chairman of the oversight committee charged with overseeing the distribution of the massive $500 billion slush fund to be given to large corporations for keeping their workers on the payroll through the pandemic rather than losing them permanently was removed. We were warned of this eventuality when Trump signed the bill; he said he did not intend to obey the part of the bill that required this oversight, stating he would perform the oversight.</p><p>Gee, what could go wrong? The most corrupt president in the history of our country in charge of literally a fortune to be distributed by him with only subordinates on the committee.</p><p>He recently removed a longtime inspector general who issued a report showing a survey of more than 300 hospital executives who overwhelmingly reported shortages of PPE, hospital beds and ventilators because the report contradicted his rosy lies that there are no shortages and the IG was appointed by President Bill Clinton.</p><p><strong>Al Weis, Hendersonville</strong></p><p><strong>Unsung heroes</strong></p><p>To the editor: While most of us are hunkered down in our homes due to COVID-19, there are many workers in our community, most of them unknown to us, who are today's heroes. They may never be mentioned in the news, as they tend to be in the background of our lives, but they, along with medical personnel and hospital workers, are also heroes worthy of recognition.</p><p>Think about the men and women such as the postal workers, newspaper home delivery people, truck drivers, UPS and FedEx delivery drivers, clerks at local gas stations, recycling and garbage collection workers, the men and women doing checkout or restocking in grocery stores, the police, ambulance drivers and firefighters, and the list goes on and on.</p><p>These heroes have selflessly placed themselves at risk of exposure to COVID-19 virus to serve those of us who are staying safely at home.</p><p>The next chance you get to interact with one of these heroes, please take a minute to simply say, \"Thank you for what you're doing for me, my family and our community.\" It'll mean a lot.</p><p><strong>Ron Kauffman, STAND T.A.L.L., Hendersonville</strong></p><p><strong>Shortsighted</strong></p><p>To the editor: The Strategic National Stockpile of N95 respirators, surgical masks and other medical supplies are nearly out. According to House Oversight Chairwoman Carolyn Maloney, \"The president failed to bring in FEMA early on, failed to name a national commander for this crisis, and failed to fully utilize the authorities Congress gave him under the Defense Production Act to procure and manage the distribution of critical supplies.\"</p><p>Instead, President Donald Trump played down the virus the first two months, calling it a \"hoax\" that was perpetrated by the Democrats and the media, and predicting as late as Feb. 26 that the number of U.S. cases would soon drop to zero. Now health care workers on the front lines are facing possible lack of protection to carry out their work.</p><p>I hope that by election time this November, Trump supporters will see that it is dangerous to our country and to the world to have such a shortsighted and self-serving person as our president and commander in chief.</p><p><strong>Connie Knight, Hendersonville</strong></p><p><strong>Incompetent</strong></p><p>To the editor: Before Donald Trump was elected president, I warned everyone in these pages that he wasn't a manager. I stated that he was just this side of a river boat gambler. A \"slam-bam, thank you, Sam\" dealer without skills for day-to-day follow-through.</p><p>Sadly, all of this has come to pass. In these extreme times, he ignored advice by science that he should act. That's when he stated that it's just like a mild flu that will be gone by April. He rejected immediate action that could have saved lives.</p><p>Our nation is down on its knees by his lack of leadership. Our economy is weakened, unemployment is skyrocketing, and companies are hemorrhaging.</p><p>While the world around us is collapsing, his thin-skinned staff took it upon themselves to add salt to the wounds and destroy the morale of one of our major weapons, the USS Theodore Roosevelt. It's dockside in Guam without a skipper.</p><p>Does anyone with Trump have any idea how the 4,000 officers and sailors are coping? Good old bone spurs in chief is at sea himself.</p><p>Is he a \"deal maker\"? Tell us about North Korea, Iran, India, China or the Palestine-Israel peace plan. Is everything in good shape here?</p><p>Trump is incompetent and can't hold a real job.</p><p><strong>Arthur Swygard, Hendersonville</strong></p>"
